{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1293"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1293"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.62,0.22,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"3975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe night intern is called to review a 65-year-old woman on the ward for hypertension, 6 hours after an elective right total knee replacement (performed under general anaesthesia). Her current blood pressure is 180/100mmHg, which has been confirmed on a manual reading in both arms. Her usual blood pressure is around 145/90mmHg. Her regular medications include perindopril and hydrochlorothiazide, which were continued peri-operatively. She denies headache, visual disturbance, chest pain, dizziness, palpitations, and dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe reports throbbing pain in her right knee at present with a pain score of 7/10. On examination, her pulse rate is 80/min, respiratory rate 14/min, oxygen saturation 97% on room air, and temperature 36.9C. She is tender to palpation over the right knee incision. Her peripheral pulses are strong. The capillary refill is less than two seconds. A bedside electrocardiogram shows sinus rhythm with no acute changes. Her pre-operative blood tests were within the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["STAT Sublingual glyceryl trinitrate","Regular simple analgesia and PRN oral oxycodone","STAT IV morphine","PRN IV Labetalol","Repeat dose of PO perindopril"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has hypertension after an elective right total knee replacement and reports postoperative right knee pain. Pain stimulates the sympathetic nervous system, which can increase blood pressure. Treating hypertension, including post-operatively, is important as it increases the risk of ischaemic episodes, cerebrovascular accidents, arrhythmias, and bleeding. In the absence of any other findings, this patient\u0027s postoperative hypertension is most likely secondary to pain and should improve with pain relief. Increased levels of pain postoperatively slow recovery and rehabilitation, and can worsen chronic post surgical pain. Managing perioperative pain is thus a key component of enhanced recovery after surgery. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular simple analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E such as paracetamol and anti-inflammatories and a PRN short-acting opioid, such as oxycodone should be employed at frequent intervals to achieve rapid analgesia in the postoperative period. This would address the pain that is likely responsible for the postoperative hypertension and as such, this is the correct answer. If the patient\u0027s blood pressure remains high despite analgesia and adequate pain relief, consideration should be given to other quick-acting anti-hypertensives, such as amlodipine, prazosin, nicardipine, labetalol and GTN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESublingual\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eglyceryl trinitrate\u003C/strong\u003E would result in rapid blood pressure control but is more commonly used in hypertensive emergencies where the patient has evidence of end-organ damage (e.g. headache, visual disturbance). It would not address the most likely cause of her hypertension (her pain) and commonly causes headaches which can be mistaken for hypertension-related headaches. For these reasons, this is not the preferred management strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV morphine\u003C/strong\u003E would address the patient\u0027s post-operative pain and likely pain-induced hypertension. However, IV morphine should not be the first analgesia in this instance. Initial regular paracetamol and PRN opioid medication should be trialled first. If these are unsuccessful, it is warranted to consider the need for stronger analgesia (e.g. IV morphine).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA beta-blocker, such as\u003Cstrong\u003E labetalol\u003C/strong\u003E,\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be intravenously infused to achieve rapid control of blood pressure. While this would treat postoperative hypertension, it would not address pain, which is the likely cause of the postoperative hypertension, thus this is an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat dose of perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is likely unnecessary if the patient\u0027s pain is adequately controlled. Furthermore, without knowing the patient\u0027s renal function repeat doses may risk renal injury with minimal benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pain is often a cause of hypertension in the postoperative period","Managing pain is one of the key components of enhanced recovery after surgery"],"references":["Korean Knee Society. Guidelines for the Management of Postoperative Pain after Total Knee Arthroplasty. Knee Surgery \u0026 Related Research. 2012 Nov 29;24(4):201\u20137.","de Ladoucette A. Management of perioperative pain after TKA. Orthop Traumatol Surg Res. 2023;109(1S):103443. doi:10.1016/j.otsr.2022.103443"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-11T19:20:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-11T19:20:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relat